A Go-based parent workflow spawns a long-running child workflow with `PARENT_CLOSE_POLICY_ABANDON` and then calls `Continue-As-New` to shed event history. The parent uses Signal and Update handlers extensively and correctly waits for `AllHandlersFinished` before throwing `NewContinueAsNewError`. After the rollout, engineers notice that **sometimes the child workflow never starts at all** — it disappears without a trace. Which interaction between Continue-As-New, child workflow lifecycle, and the Abandon policy explains this behavior?

```go
func ParentWorkflow(ctx workflow.Context, input Input) error {
    cwo := workflow.ChildWorkflowOptions{
        ParentClosePolicy: enums.PARENT_CLOSE_POLICY_ABANDON,
    }
    ctx2 := workflow.WithChildOptions(ctx, cwo)
    childFuture := workflow.ExecuteChildWorkflow(ctx2, ChildWorkflow, input.ChildParams)
    // ... handle signals/updates ...
    if shouldContinueAsNew(ctx) {
        return workflow.NewContinueAsNewError(ctx, ParentWorkflow, nextInput)
    }
    return childFuture.Get(ctx, nil)
}
```

An engineering team maintains a .NET workflow that manages a long-lived cluster. It uses Update handlers extensively for node assignment operations and calls `Continue-As-New` when `Workflow.ContinueAsNewSuggested` is true. To test this, they set `TestContinueAsNew = true` in CI, which reduces `maxHistoryLength` to 5. In CI, the workflow intermittently panics during replay with a non-determinism error **only when an Update arrives concurrently with the Continue-As-New decision**. Which interaction between Update handlers, the `AllHandlersFinished` guard, and the Continue-As-New test hook explains this failure?

```csharp
private bool ShouldContinueAsNew =>
    Workflow.AllHandlersFinished &&
    (Workflow.ContinueAsNewSuggested || Workflow.CurrentHistoryLength > maxHistoryLength);

// In main loop:
if (ShouldContinueAsNew)
    throw Workflow.CreateContinueAsNewException(...);
```
